      <div xml:id="NA262-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaḷ āṟṟāk kuṟippaṟintu piriviṭai vilakkiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how SHE blocks in the middle of the separation, having understood [HIS] intention, being unable to bear it.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA262">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            taṇpuṉak karuviḷaik kaṇpōṉ māmala</l>
<l>            rāṭumayiṟ pīliyiṉ vāṭaiyoṭu tuyalvara</l>
<l>            vuṟaimayak kuṟṟa vūrtuñ ciyāmattu</l>
<l>            naṭuṅkupiṇi naliya nalleḻil cāayt</l>
<l>            tuṉikūr maṉattaṇ muṉipaṭa ruḻakkum </l>
<l>            paṇaittō ḷarumpiya cuṇaṅkiṟ kaṇaikkāṟ</l>
<l>            kuvaḷai nāṟuṅ kūntaṟ ṟēmoḻi</l>
<l>            yivaḷiṟ ṟīrntu māḷviṉai valippap</l>
<l>            pirivi ṉeñceṉṉu māyi</l>
<l>            ṉaritumaṉ ṟamma viḷamaiya tiḷivē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Severe indeed, alas, [is] the abuse(?) of youth<note place="foot">Here it is difficult to decide between the variants. Most printed editions read <term xml:lang="ta">iṉmaiyatu</term> (which might be interpreted as "poverty") instead of iḷamaiyatu, in fact the spelling of these two is so close that it might be difficult to distinguish. In any case, both are topoi: HE has to go, because having nothing is unworthy, and if he goes, he mourns the waste of youth.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">when the heart speaks of separation,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">piriviṉ neñcu eṉṉum</term>: here again we have several variants and all of them seem possible (apart from some misspelled letters in G1+2). Best attested seems <term xml:lang="ta">pirivaṉ neñcu eṉṉum</term>, "the heart says ‘I will separate’", but even ET’s <term xml:lang="ta">pirivu naṉṟu eṉṉum</term> "it is said that separation [is] something good" is not inconceivable.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">as manly work is compelling, even leaving her</l>
<l rend="indent">with honey words [and] tresses that are fragrant of round-stemmed</l>
<l rend="indent">blue waterlilies, with beauty spots that budded on [her] bamboo shoulder,</l>
<l rend="indent">who will bear hateful affliction, her mind filled with disgust,</l>
<l rend="indent">[her] good grace being exhausted while afflicted by the shivering disease,</l>
<l rend="indent3">at midnight when the village sleeps, perturbed by drops,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that the eye-like dark blossoms of the Karuviḷai in the cool fields</l>
<l rend="indent2">come into swinging with the north wind as the feathers</l>
<l rend="indent2">of a dancing peacock.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
